The second most likely sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory), as the paper discusses tools from probability theory such as random variables and expectations, concentration bounds, and Markov chains. The third most likely sub-category is cs.CC (Computational Complexity), as the paper covers derandomization and quantum computing. The fourth most likely sub-category is cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics), as the paper discusses the Lovasz Local Lemma and randomized approximate counting. The fifth most likely sub-category is cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), as the paper covers Markov chain Monte Carlo sampling, which is a common technique in machine learning and AI.
